John Edward: Language skills essential for world citizens
Scotland’s independent schools continue to be distinguished by academic excellence, which continued in 2018 with further outstanding examination results and is only backed up by individual and joint achievements in the fields of sports, art, music and other collaborative ventures.
With more than 30,000 students from all over Scotland, these schools represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) strive to care for their students and their parents at the highest possible level.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for further education and higher education, the profession of their choice and their place as world citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement a tailor-made curriculum, we see that modern languages are still popular and sought after in schools as electives.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to someone in a language he understands, you reach his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, you reach his heart.”
This is an impressive reminder that we can’t rely only on English if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
The current results of this year’s exam show that languages with the highest pass rates are at the top of the rankings of independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who learned foreign languages scored A at the higher exams.
The data collected by 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students in Mandarin scored grade A at the higher exams, while 72 percent of students learning German, 69 percent of students learning French, and 63 percent of students learning Spanish also scored grade A.
This illustrates that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as an important knowledge that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now regarded as electives as well as STEM subjects (natural sciences, engineering, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and elsewhere.
According to a 2014 survey by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills, 17 percent of the reasons employers cited for occupying vacancies were related to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly imperative when it comes to preparing young people for their future profession.
As more and more vacancies require languages, this knowledge is essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the chosen profession, young people who have learned a second language will have a real advantage in the future through such a lifelong skill.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically give multilingual people an edge over competitors.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation, and French was spoken as the only language of a double-digit percentage (15 percent).
For this reason, it is important for today’s children that we invest in language lessons now.
Children who speak multiple languages, especially languages of developing countries, will have better chances of finding meaningful employment.
In Scotland, different languages are taught at all schools.
A number of schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered the most important for the UK in 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Wherever your child’s interests lie, independent schools will always have a number of languages with appropriately specialized teachers to choose from.
Scottish independent schools are committed to creating a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills necessary for their success, whatever the future may look like.
At this time in a global economic environment, it cannot be denied that languages are still of fundamental importance for the future of the country, which is why this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should actually be regarded as ‘international communication skills’.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
It is very fair.
