“We don’t see any response from the United States,” he said.
“Without confidence in the US, there is no confidence in our national security, and under these circumstances, we will not unilaterally disarm ourselves first.”
While Ri repeated trusted complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “phased” denuclearization approach, which rewarded North Korea for successive steps, his statement seemed significant in that it did not reject a one-sided denuclearization from the outset, as Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first summit between an incumbent U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, in which Kim had promised to work towards “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula,” while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea’s security.
North Korea is seeking an official end to the Korean War from 1950 to 1953, while the United States has said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
In addition, Washington opposes calls for a loosening of severe international sanctions against North Korea.
“The U.S. insists on ‘first denuclearization’ and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal by force, and is even opposed to the ‘explanation of the end of the war,’ Ri said.
“The assumption that sanctions can force us to our knees is a fantasy of the people who know nothing about us.
The problem, however, is that the continued sanctions deepen our distrust.”
Ri did not comment on plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the U.S. head of state had highlighted earlier this week at the United Nations.
Instead, the minister pointed to three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If South Korea were the other party in the denuclearization issue instead of the US, it would not have come to a halt in the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula.”
Nevertheless, the tone of Ri’s speech was vastly different from his speech last year when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to target the U.S. with North Korea’s missiles after “evil president” Trump described Kim as a “missile man” on suicide mission.
This year, Trump, who threatened North Korea’s “total destruction” last year, praised Kim at the United Nations for his courage to take disarmament steps, but said there was still a lot of work to be done and the sanctions needed to remain in place until North Korea’s denuclearization.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no time frame for it: “Whether it’s two years, three years, or five months – it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council must reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday: “Enforcement of the Security Council’s sanctions must in any case continue vigorously until we have reached full, final and verified denuclearization.”
Since 2006, the Security Council has unanimously stepped up sanctions against North Korea to financially dry out Pyongyang’s nuclear weapons and ballistic missile programs.
