Harvard students learn enough sleep in a course
A new course at Harvard University ensures that all undergraduate students get more sleep this year. This is a measure against the spreading macho culture of staying awake with caffeine and learning all night.
One scientist has found that students at the world’s leading university are often unnecessary when it comes to taking care of themselves.
Designed by Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, the course is the first such course in the United States.
He was inspired to initiate the course after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At the end of the day, a girl came to me and asked, ‘Why am I only learning about it now, in my last year?’
She said no one had ever told her how important sleep is, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
This year’s first course explained to students how the basics of good sleep habits contribute to academic and athletic performance and also improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university chose to launch the course after finding that students were suffering from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a range of interactive tasks.
In one section, students see the picture of a room in a dormitory and click on coffee mugs, curtains, training shoes and books to get information about the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the effects of lack of sleep on athletic performance and the importance of a sleep routine.
In another section, participants learn that long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, and cancer.
Afterwards, they are encouraged to think about their daily routine with interactive symbols using a map of the university grounds.
“We know it won’t change the behavior of students right away.
But we believe they have the right to know – just as you have the right to know how the decision to smoke affects your health,” added Professor Czeisler.
The pride of pushing a “night shift” is still widespread, he said, adding that modern technologies and the ever-growing pressure on students make the lack of sleep a growing problem.
Ensuring enough sleep should be the “secret weapon” of all students against stress, exhaustion and anxiety, and weight gain could be avoided as sleep deprivation puts the brain in hunger mode, causing them to be constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student from California who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, having taken one of his courses last year in his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and encouraged him to push for a university-wide course.
He hopes that in the next step, all postgraduate students will be asked to complete a similar study program before they begin their studies at the competitive university.
According to Professor Czeisler, students should face an alarm for bedtime and wake-up time and be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emanating from electronic screens and LED lights, which can take the circadian rhythm off the beat. This leads to problems when falling asleep.
