National Trust listens to the secret life of bats
In an estate in the Scottish Highlands, new research is being carried out to show how bats use the landscape in food hunting.
It is hoped that the results will provide further insights into the behavior of these unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
The study, conducted by researchers at the National Trust for Scotland, will track down dwarf and mosquito bats as well as the brown long ear and water bats at Inverewe Garden in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices are placed at key locations on the property to record the activities of the bats throughout the season.
NHS employees and volunteers will also conduct mobile investigations using portable detectors.
In the case of a noise analysis of all recordings by experts, the frequency of the bat calls is determined and determines which species does what.
A map and a report of the habitat is then created to create a detailed picture of their behavior at the landscape level.
Rob Dewar, nature conservation consultant for the NTS, hopes that the results will show which areas of habitat are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
These data will help determine the benefits of habitat management measures, such as creating meadows, and show how to preserve forest areas for bats and other related species.
Fledermaus stocks in Scotland and the whole of the United Kingdom have decreased significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affect sleeping places and lead to habitat loss.
Windmills and lighting can also pose a risk, as can flycatchers and the chemical treatment of building materials or also attacks by domestic cats.
Bats are not really blind.
However, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey due to their nighttime hunting habits.
They use sophisticated ultrasound mapping to detect insects and obstacles in their trajectory.
The NTS, responsible for the care of over 270 historic buildings, 38 significant gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout Scotland, takes the theme of bats very seriously.
He has 10 trained experts who carry out regular examinations, inspections of sleeping places, and sometimes rescues.
The organization has even set up Scotland’s first and only bat reserve at the Threave property in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland’s 10 bat species.
Estate manager David Thompson explains that the property is the ideal habitat for them.
“Here in Threave we have a great area for bats,” he explains.
“We have the old buildings, many old trees and an excellent habitat.
But there’s a lot we don’t know about bats yet, so we’re doing this work here and on other goods that will help us learn more about what bats need to feel comfortable.”
He stresses the importance of first excluding the presence of bats before maintenance work in the goods, as it is possible that the involuntary destruction of a single nesting site could kill up to 400 females and young animals and wipe out the entire population on site.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, harass them or destroy them or their nesting areas.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish official of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the population to help.
She explains: “We still have a lot to learn about bats and for many of our species we don’t know what their populations are like.”
