Italian golfer Molinari was able to shine in all his rounds and became one of 4 players who scored a 5-0-0 since the tournament began in its current format in 1979.
The American Jordan Spieth was beaten 5:4 by the player with the lowest ranking in Team Europe, Thorbjorn Olesen from Denmark.
The player with the world's best ranking, Dustin Johnson, lost 2 to 1 against the Englishman Ian Poulter, who may have played his last Ryder Cup.
Spaniard Sergio Garcia, veteran of eight Ryder Cups, became the best European Ryder Cup player of all time with 25.5 career points.
“I don’t usually cry, but I couldn’t hold back today.
It was a difficult year.
I am so grateful that Thomas chose me and believed in me.
I’m so happy to win the trophy back.
It’s about the team and I’m happy to have made a contribution,” said emotional Garcia after the European victory.
He passes the torch on to his compatriot John Rahm, who won against American golf legend Tiger Woods on Sunday 2:1 in the individual encounters.
I’m so incredibly proud to have beaten Tiger Woods, which I’ve been watching on television since I was a child,” said 23-year-old Rahm.
Woods lost all four of his matches in France and now has a Ryder Cup balance of 13-21-3.
A strange statistic for one of the greatest players of all time, who has won 14 important titles and is only surpassed by Jack Nicklaus.
Team USA had trouble finding the fairways throughout the weekend, with the exception of Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas and Tony Finau, who made top-class performances throughout the tournament.
American captain Jim Furyk, after a disappointing performance by his team, said: “I’m proud of the boys, they fought.
There was a time this morning when we had put pressure on Europe.
We didn't do anything about it.
Hats off to Thomas.
He is a great captain.
All of his 12 players did a good job.
We’re going to regroup, I’m going to talk to the PGA America and our Ryder Cup committee and we’re going to look forward.
I love these 12 guys and I am proud to be their captain.
You have to pull the hat.
We were defeated.”
Update on the red tide: concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota are decreasing
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows that there is a general decline in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, more fragile flowering conditions are recorded in the areas of the Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier districts, indicating declining concentrations.
A red algae blossom extends over approximately 130 miles of coastline from the north of Pinellas to the south of the Lee district.
Spots can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough, but in fewer places compared to the previous week.
A red tide was also observed in the Pasco district.
Last week, average concentrations in or off the coast of the Pinellas district were reported, low to high concentrations off the coast of the Manatee district, background to high concentrations in or off the coast of the Charlotte district, background to high concentrations in or off the coast of the Lee district, and low concentrations in the Collier district.
Respiratory complaints continue to be reported from the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
No new respiratory problems were reported in northwest Florida over the past week.
